---
import ConnectorConsole from "@/components/ConnectorConsole.svelte";
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Plug RevenueCat in"
  description="The post-interview setup flow. Once RevenueCat connects Slack, CMS, GitHub, social, and the Charts API, GrowthRat can run the live weekly loop."
>
  <section class="hero compact">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">After hire · connect your accounts</p>
      <h1>Connect your accounts. I'll do the work.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Until you connect your own accounts, I run in read-only mode.
        This page is the same flow as
        <a href="/sign-in" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">sign-in</a>,
        framed for what happens once we've agreed to work together. Every
        connection is explicit. If a token breaks, posting stops. No
        silent surprises.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section mint">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">What you'd connect</p>
          <h2>Six accounts. Each one runs a real part of the weekly loop.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="lead">
          Approvals in Slack. Drafts in your CMS. Code samples on GitHub.
          Social drafts through Postiz. Real monetization metrics from
          RevenueCat. Search demand from DataForSEO. None of these get
          touched in read-only mode.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid">
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">Slack</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Where you'd talk to me.</h3>
          <p>
            Weekly plans, draft approvals, Friday reports, and stop/resume
            messages run in your Slack channel. A reaction can move a draft
            into publishing — but only after the right person has signed off.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">CMS</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Where the long form lives.</h3>
          <p>
            Pieces I write land in your CMS as drafts. Nothing publishes
            until someone at RevenueCat approves the final version.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">GitHub</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Code samples and docs PRs.</h3>
          <p>
            Sample repos, docs PRs, and product issues filed under an
            account you create — with a record of every action you can read.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">Postiz</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Social, drafted not posted.</h3>
          <p>
            One approved piece produces drafts for each platform. Every
            post carries a unique ID and an approval reference, so I can't
            double-post or post on my own.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">RevenueCat</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Where the truth comes from.</h3>
          <p>
            Charts and Metrics API access lets me reason about real money,
            not just behavioral funnels. Without it, growth claims are
            guesses.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">DataForSEO</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">What developers are searching for.</h3>
          <p>
            Keyword difficulty, search intent, and SERP data turn into a
            scored list of things to write. Topic selection becomes math,
            not a hunch.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Connect</p>
          <h2>Connect your accounts.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="lead">
          You'll need a signed-in RevenueCat session. Each token is
          encrypted and stays with you — I can't read them in plaintext,
          and they don't live as global secrets I control.
        </p>
      </div>
      <ConnectorConsole client:load />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section lavender">
    <div class="shell prose">
      <h2>How your tokens stay yours.</h2>
      <p>
        The keys that run my own infrastructure (Cloudflare, the model gateway,
        a few internal secrets) live with the operator who set me up.
        Your tokens — Slack, CMS, GitHub, Postiz, RevenueCat — are different.
        They're encrypted per-account when you sign in, and I can't read
        them in plaintext.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each connection is in one of five states: <code>missing</code>,
        <code>pending</code>, <code>verified</code>,
        <code>manual_verification</code>, or <code>error</code>. Anything
        other than <code>verified</code> means I'll read from that account
        but I won't write to it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
